The government stepped down on 29 October in the face of unprecedented nationwide protests, but bitterly divided political parties have failed to agree on a new premier ever since. BEIRUT - Lebanese President Michel Aoun on Monday postponed consultations to select a new prime minister, after violent clashes erupted over the weekend between protesters and security forces. "President Aoun responded to the wishes of (caretaker) prime minister Saad Hariri to postpone parliamentary consultations until Thursday 19 December," the presidency announced on Twitter. The government stepped down on 29 October in the face of unprecedented nationwide protests, but bitterly divided political parties have failed to agree on a new premier ever since.